{{en-noun}}

# A [[tool]] for [[fell]]ing trees or [[chop]]ping wood etc. consisting of a heavy <!-- [[metallic]] (material is not essential, the axes used to be of stone in the stone age --> [[head]] [[flatten]]ed to a [[blade]] on one side, and a <!-- usually wooden (material is not essential) --> [[handle]] attached to it.
# An [[ancient]] [[weapon]] consisting of a <!-- [[metallic]] --> [[head]] that has one or two [[blade]]s and a long [[handle]].
# {{informal}} A dismissal or rejection.
#: His girlfriend/boss/[[schoolmaster]] gave him the '''axe'''.
#* '''1975''', {{w|Bob Dylan}}, {{w|Tangled Up in Blue}}
#*: I had a job in the great North Woods
#*: Workin' as a cook for a spell.
#*: But I never did like it all that much
#*: And one day the '''axe''' just fell.
# {{slang|music}} A [[gig|gigging]] musician's particular instrument, especially a [[guitar]] in [[rock]] music or a [[saxophone]] in jazz.
# {{finance}} A directional position or interest, by a [[dealer]] in a financial market – if one wishes to unload stock, one is “axed to sell” or “has an axe”.<ref>[http://www.risk.net/public/showPage.html?page=132529 Shedding the correlation ‘axe’], Risk magazine</ref> Derived from “[[have an axe to grind]]”, which is also used.

